 # May 14, 2026 

    Thought I had it all situated I thought wrong. Doing further testing requests were still coming in causing memory leaks.

    ** THE FIX

        I decided to try a locking system using a Mutex.
        With JavaScript being a tank when it comes to treating concurrency once one protected route request comes in with an expired token 5 more come behind. 
        Causing the verifyToken middleware to fire and notice that all 5 request come in with a valid refresh token. So what I am hoping for is by using a Mutex 
        using their Id as the key will lock any other requests coming from said key processing them one by one. 
        But since I don't want all of the request to generate a new token another condition is set 

    Using the re-use abuse monitor I am also verifying whether it's just a different token, using the given token's payload to the currently stored one
    hopefully how it's working in my brain the current stored token will be the used sort of like the updated state, not too sure though.

